Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

Observations of Summary Data:

  • The dataset has 1599 observations.
  • Each observation represents a red wine and that red wine has 11 attributes 1.fixed acidity, 2.volatile acidity, 3.citric acid, 4.residual sugar, 5.chlorides, 6.free sulfur dioxide, 7.total sulfur dioxide, 8.density, 9.pH, 10.sulphates, 11.alcohol,
  • Red wine has 1 output variable 1.red wine quality

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

The main interesting feature is the wine quality. It is the subjective measurement of how attractive the wine might be to a consumer. The goal here will be to try and correlate non-subjective wine properties with its quality.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

Many measurements that were clustered close to zero had a positive skew. Others such as pH and total.acidity and quality had normal lookingdistributions.

Bivariate Plots Section

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest c with other features in
the dataset?

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features
(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

  • There is a relationship between sulphates and wine qualtity, particularly if you disregard extreme sulphate values
  • Disregarding measurements where sulphates > 1.0 is the same as disregarding the positive tail of the distribution, keeping just the normal-looking portion
  • The relationship is a week one

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The strongest relationship between wine properties and wine quality was that of alcohol, chlorides and citric acid.

Multivariate Plots Section

Multivariate Analysis

• The strongest relationship between wine properties and wine quality was that of alcohol, chlorides and citric acid • pH is considered important when assessing wine quality, however the data does not show an appreciable correlation. In fact, any correlations are week ones. • The model built with alcohol, chlorides, citric acid, residual sugar and total acidity featured a low R-squared value of just 0.3. Compared with a model where we just start with a guess of the median wine quality (R-squared of 0.5), the model performs rathe poorly. • Often, the tails of property distributions showed a varied relationship with quality.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

### Description One This plot shows the complete picture of the analysis of win quality with two important notes: 1. Alcohol content has some effect on wine quality rating 2. The effect is not a strong one

you can almost see in this visualization the distribution shuffle from left to right as wine ratings increase.

Plot Two

Description Two

This plot illustrates that there was little to no correlation between wine quality and percentage of volume. Additionally, in each case, there are outlier ratings that undermine the general relationship.

Plot Three

Description Three

citric acid seems to have the most promeneant effect on wine quality. There is a specific bump at around 0.25 where the wine quality jumps up in the rating. That bump was also present in the univariate distribution plot for citric acid

When plotted against wine quality in a scatter plot like this, only citric acid and alcohol displayed a noticeable trend. In each case, the distribution is slightly skewed towards higher citric acid and higher quality.

Reflection

I don’t have any knowledge about wine before this project, so I didn’t have any expectation or assumption. Initially, nothing was immediately correlate to be an inherent quality of good wines. However, upon reflection, this is a practical finding.

I found out after this project that alcohol content and citric acid were the most properties to wine quality.

I was not able to find a strong set of two properties that would consistently be able to predict wine quality with any degree of certainty.

Additionally, having the wine type would be helpful for further analysis.
